# NightStrike Firmware - Cursor Rules

## Project Context
This is NightStrike-Firmware - an advanced ESP32 firmware for offensive security operations and Black Hat activities.

## Architecture
- Modular design with interface-based modules
- Modern C++17/20, RAII principles
- Error handling via Error codes (no exceptions)
- Namespace organization: NightStrike::Core, NightStrike::Modules, NightStrike::Utils
- Singleton pattern for system components

## Code Style
- camelCase for methods, PascalCase for classes
- Use Error type for error handling (not exceptions)
- All modules implement IModule interface
- Use LOG_INFO(), LOG_ERROR() macros for logging
- Follow existing patterns in codebase

## Key Components
- Core: System, Config, Errors, Display, Input, Menu, Storage, Network, WebUI, Logger, PowerManagement
- Modules: WiFi (100%), BLE (75%), RF (65%), RFID (65%), BlackHat Tools (55%)
- Utils: String utilities, logging system

## Important Files
- src/main.cpp - Entry point
- src/core/ - Core system components
- src/modules/ - Feature modules
- include/ - Header files
- platformio.ini - Project configuration

## When Adding New Code
1. Follow existing architecture patterns
2. Implement IModule interface for new modules
3. Use Error type for error handling
4. Add unit tests
5. Update documentation
6. Use appropriate namespace

## Security
- No hardcoded passwords
- Mandatory password change on first boot
- Password validation required
- Secure configuration storage

## Testing
- Use Unity framework
- Add unit tests for new components
- Integration tests for modules

## Documentation
- Update docs/ when adding features
- Add examples to docs/EXAMPLES.md
- Document API in headers

